ENUGU – An unnamed official of the Independent National Electoral Commission, INEC, has been seen on camera asking for money before handing out Permanent Voter Cards to their owners. In the video seen by Sundiata Post, the incident happened at Emene primary school, Enugu East local government area of Enugu State. From the video, which is currently making the rounds online, the INEC official told the voters that the money was for her transportation to the local government from where they were supposed to pick up their cards. One of the men that spoke in the video accused the yet to be official of hijacking their PVC with the claim that its in the local government secretariat and asked them to pay her N1,000. Official of the electoral commission is yet to react to the incident. Watch the video below: By Stanley Nwanosike   Enugu   -     The Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) says it has concluded arrangements to move its staff to the 260 wards in Enugu State to distribute 405,000 Permanent Voters Cards (PVCs). “We are going to move over 500 personnel, comprising 400 staff and over 40 corps… In "News" By Stanley Nwanosike   Enugu,   -      The Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) on Thursday said 200,000 Permanent Voters Cards (PVCs) were still uncollected in Enugu state, and urged concerned people to pick up the cards. The Resident Electoral Commissioner (REC) in the state, Mr Emeka Ononamadu, made… In "News" Enugu -   The Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC), has urged traditional rulers in Enugu State to caution their subjects against violence and violation of the electoral guidelines. Mr Festus Okoye, INEC’s National Commissioner for Anambra and Enugu States, made the appeal during an interactive session with the traditional rulers… In "Politics"